###### Multi-Container Shared Volume #######

Real Kubernetes power starts here.

Scenario

Application writes logs.

Log collector reads logs.

Architecture:

Container 1
(Application)
      |
 shared volume
      |
Container 2
(Log Collector)
Lab

Create:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod

metadata:
  name: multi-container

spec:

  containers:

  - name: writer
    image: busybox

    command:
      - sh
      - -c
      - while true; do date >> /shared/log.txt; sleep 5; done

    volumeMounts:
    - name: shared-storage
      mountPath: /shared

  - name: reader
    image: busybox

    command:
      - sh
      - -c
      - tail -f /shared/log.txt

    volumeMounts:
    - name: shared-storage
      mountPath: /shared

  volumes:
  - name: shared-storage
    emptyDir: {}

Apply:

kubectl apply -f multi.yaml

Check reader logs:

kubectl logs multi-container -c reader

Output:

Mon Jul 21 10:01:01 UTC
Mon Jul 21 10:01:06 UTC
Mon Jul 21 10:01:11 UTC
Real-World Example

Before:

Application
|
Local Logs

Problem:

Logs Lost

Enterprise Solution:

Application
    |
 emptyDir
    |
Fluent Bit Sidecar
    |
ElasticSearch

This pattern is used everywhere.

Part 5: hostPath Volume

Dangerous but important.

hostPath mounts node filesystem into Pod.

Architecture

Worker Node
|
/data
|
Pod

Example

volumes:
- name: host-storage

  hostPath:
    path: /data

Mount:

volumeMounts:
- mountPath: /host-data
  name: host-storage

Verify:

kubectl exec -it hostpath-demo -- ls /host-data

You will see node files.

Why hostPath is Dangerous

Pod gets access to:

Node Filesystem

Potential risks:

Security Issues
Node Manipulation
Data Corruption
Interview Question

Should hostPath be used in production?

Answer:

Generally No.

Only for:
Monitoring Agents
Node Exporters
Special Use Cases
